debrief.1: I believe it was, as a whole, trying to look into participants' decision-making strategies (for example, did the color of the potential classmate make a difference? Did they try to discover patterns?). Along these lines, I think it was also looking into how participants' improvised when faced with continuous failures (when points were subtracted).
debrief.2: I began by choosing each classmate once, to try to get a better idea of who was more trustworthy. When a classmate ended up failing to help me, I would see if there was a pattern (i.e., when suddenly the blue classmate began not helping, I sometimes noticed that the black classmate began to help).
debrief.3: To some extent, but only when I noticed patterns (for example, if I noticed that one classmate seemed to help consecutively in groupings of 4-5 decisions, I would try switching to the other classmate who seemed to help when the other did not (i.e., on the 5th or 6th decision).
